Rating: 1
Followed this recipe pretty close to the original as those were the ingredients I had on hand and the reason I chose to try this recipe. In short it should be avoided. The flavor was not too bad after a few tweaks. After finishing off the remainder of the wine I was able to choke a bowl of it down. The chicken took on a comically purple tint, the texture was terrible, I really wish I had that cup of wine back.

Rating: 4
Great, simple and easy. I threw in some yukon gold potatoes to thicken it up a bit and also let it simmer about half an hour longer than suggested. Will definitely make this again.

Rating: 0
"1 tbsp olive oil "4 cloves of garlic, mashed "1 cup chopped tomatoes "2 boneless chicken breasts cut into 2" cubes "1 sliced onion "1 cup sliced mushrooms "3/4 cup madeira plus 1/4 cup balsamic vinegar "1 cup chicken stock (1 cup water plus 1/2 chicken or vegetable bouillon cube) "1/2 tsp thyme 1/4 tsp red pepper flakes -------------------------------I thought this recipe seemed like it would need more flavor, as did some other reviewers, so I adjusted it as above. The extra garlic and red pepper flakes gave it more pizzaz, and using madeira instead of plain red wine gave it a richer flavor. This would also be great with boneless, skinless thighs.It was a big hit.

Rating: 3
I agree with HollyW, its good recipe to play with. I used less wine, added some flour close to end to make it more thick and also used basil. I decided not to use parmesan and was not missing it. Served with homemade crispy bread and got success. Next time i will probably also add shallot to the stew.

Rating: 3
Also, you can try cutting the wine a bit and adding balsamic vinegar-a couple tbsps or so to taste, if you like that balsamic-y flavor more

Rating: 3
This can be a very tasty recipe, if you play with it a little. I used green onions and used rosemary instead of thyme-though i'm sure it'd be good w/both. Also added lots of freshly ground pepper and some parmesan cheese and fresh torn basil as garnish. I served it with sliced crusty bread, lightly buttered and baked at 350 for 10min, then rubbed with a garlic clove. That REALLY made the dish.

